SIMPLE: sift
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sift
<hw>Sift</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sifted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sifting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>siftan</ets>, from
<ets>sife</ets> sieve. ⟦root⟧151<it>a</it>. See <er>Sieve</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To separate with a sieve, as the fine part of a
substance from the coarse; <as>as, to <ex>sift</ex> meal or flour; to
<ex>sift</ex> powder; to <ex>sift</ex> sand or lime.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To separate or part as if with a sieve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When yellow sands are <qex>sifted</qex> from below,⟦br⟧
The glittering billows give a golden show.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To examine critically or minutely; to
scrutinize.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sifting</qex> the very utmost sentence and syllable.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Opportunity I here have had⟦br⟧
To try thee, <qex>sift</qex> thee.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let him but narrowly <qex>sift</qex> his ideas.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To sift out</b></col>, <cd>to search out with care, as if
by sifting.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sifter</ent>⟦br⟧
